        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>402</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000L</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000L.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Arzelà-Ascoli Theorem">Arzelà-Ascoli Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let K be a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000H.xml" addr="FA-000H" title="Compact">compact</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000G.xml" addr="FA-000G" title="Metric Space">metric space</fr:link>. A subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(K)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000I.xml" addr="FA-000I" title="Precompact">precompact</fr:link> if and only if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000J.xml" addr="FA-000J" title="Bounded">bounded</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000K.xml" addr="FA-000K" title="Equicontinuous">equicontinuous</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>N.B</fr:strong> since uniform equicontinuity implies pointwise equicontinuity, the usage of "equicontious" above is unambiguous.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If that subset is closed, then it's <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000H.xml" addr="FA-000H" title="Compact">compact</fr:link></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>403</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000I</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000I.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Precompact">Precompact</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to be precompact (or relatively compact) if its closure is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000H.xml" addr="FA-000H" title="Compact">compact</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, a set is precompact if every sequence in the set has a convergent subsequence in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> (though the limit might not be in the original set).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In a complete metric space, a set is precompact if and only if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000O.xml" addr="FA-000O" title="Totally bounded">totally bounded</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
