        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>404</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000N</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000N.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Complete">Complete</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to be complete if every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000X.xml" addr="FA-000X" title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> converges to a point in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Intuitively, a metric space is complete if there are no "holes" or "missing points" in it. All the limit points of Cauchy sequences are already in the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples of complete spaces include <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> with the Euclidean metric, <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach spaces</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>405</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000P</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000P.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Heine-Borel Theorem">Heine-Borel Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000M.xml" addr="FA-000M" title="Sequentially compact">sequentially compact</fr:link> <fr:em>if and only if</fr:em> it is closed and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000J.xml" addr="FA-000J" title="Bounded">bounded</fr:link></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>406</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000M</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000M.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Sequentially compact">Sequentially compact</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a topological space is sequentially compact if every sequence in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> has a convergent subsequence whose limit is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In metric spaces, sequential compactness is equivalent to compactness.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, a set is sequentially compact if and only if it is closed and bounded (the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000P.xml" addr="FA-000P" title="Heine-Borel Theorem">Heine-Borel Theorem</fr:link>).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>407</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000O</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000O.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Totally bounded">Totally bounded</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to be totally bounded if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists a finite cover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> by balls of radius <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exist finitely many points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_1, x_2, \ldots , x_n \in  X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \subseteq  \cup _{i=1}^n B(x_i, ε)]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B(x_i, ε)]]></fr:tex> is the ball with center <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_i]]></fr:tex> and radius <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In a complete metric space, a set is compact if and only if it is totally bounded and closed.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
